00:19:06,115 --> 00:19:09,790
JAMlE: Come on, Alfie, let's go 'ome now.
This place is givin' me the willies.

240
00:19:09,875 --> 00:19:11,991
Home? What do you want to go 'ome for?

241
00:19:12,075 --> 00:19:15,431
lt's nearly 5:00.
My daughter Eliza'll be along soon.

242
00:19:15,675 --> 00:19:18,712
She ought to be good for 'alf a crown
for a father that loves 'er.

243
00:19:18,795 --> 00:19:21,514
HARRY: That's a laugh.
You ain't been near 'er for months.

244
00:19:21,595 --> 00:19:25,224
What's that got to do with it?
What's 'alf a crown after all l've give 'er?

245
00:19:25,315 --> 00:19:27,271
When did you ever give 'er anythin'?

246
00:19:27,355 --> 00:19:29,425
Anythin'? l give 'er everythin'.

247
00:19:29,515 --> 00:19:33,144
l give 'er the greatest gift
any human being can give to another:

248
00:19:33,235 --> 00:19:34,190
Life!

249
00:19:34,595 --> 00:19:38,793
l introduced 'er to this here planet, l did,
with all its wonders and marvels.

250
00:19:38,955 --> 00:19:41,389
The sun that shines, the moon that glows.

251
00:19:41,595 --> 00:19:44,348
Hyde Park to walk through
on a fine spring night.

252
00:19:44,715 --> 00:19:48,867
The 'ole ruddy city o' London to roam
around in sellin' 'er bloomin' flow'rs.

253
00:19:49,075 --> 00:19:50,508
l give 'er all that.

254
00:19:51,275 --> 00:19:54,028
Then l disappears and leaves 'er
on 'er own to enjoy it.

255
00:19:54,115 --> 00:19:56,310
lf that ain't worth 'alf a crown
now and again...

256
00:19:56,395 --> 00:19:58,465
...l'll take my belt off and give 'er what for.

257
00:19:58,555 --> 00:20:01,627
You got a good 'eart.
But you want a 'alf a crown out o' Eliza...

258
00:20:01,715 --> 00:20:03,353
...you better have a good story.

259
00:20:03,435 --> 00:20:05,505
ALFlE: Leave that to me, my boy.

260
00:20:05,835 --> 00:20:08,713
-Good mornin', George.
-Not a brass farthin'.

261
00:20:15,595 --> 00:20:17,551
ALGERNON: Not a brass farthin'.

262
00:20:24,635 --> 00:20:26,626
[Soft instrumental music]

263
00:21:00,835 --> 00:21:03,668
[Fast-paced instrumental music]

264
00:21:35,275 --> 00:21:36,424
There she is.

265
00:21:44,595 --> 00:21:46,665
Why, Liza, what a surprise.

266
00:21:47,715 --> 00:21:50,548
Hop along, Charlie, you're too old for me.

267
00:21:50,955 --> 00:21:53,753
-Don't you know your daughter?
-You don't know what she looks like.

268
00:21:53,835 --> 00:21:56,554
l know 'er, l know 'er.
Come on, l'll find 'er.

269
00:21:58,635 --> 00:22:01,911
[lnstrumental version of
Wouldn't It Be Loverly]

270
00:22:24,755 --> 00:22:26,234
Eliza, what a surprise.

271
00:22:26,315 --> 00:22:27,828
Not a brass farthin'.

272
00:22:27,995 --> 00:22:30,031
Hey, you come 'ere, Eliza.

273
00:22:30,315 --> 00:22:32,465
l ain't gonna take me 'ard-earned wages...

274
00:22:32,555 --> 00:22:35,308
...and let you pass 'em on
to a bloody pubkeeper.

275
00:22:42,315 --> 00:22:45,227
You wouldn't send me 'ome
to your stepmother...

276
00:22:45,315 --> 00:22:48,193
...without a drop o' liquid protection,
would ya?

277
00:22:48,275 --> 00:22:49,993
Stepmother, indeed!

278
00:22:50,395 --> 00:22:53,387
Well, l'm willin' to marry 'er.
lt's me that suffers by it.

279
00:22:53,475 --> 00:22:55,466
l'm a slave to that woman, Eliza.

280
00:22:55,555 --> 00:22:58,308
Just because l ain't 'er lawful 'usband.

281
00:22:58,595 --> 00:22:59,584
Come on.

282
00:22:59,675 --> 00:23:02,587
Slip your ol' dad just 'alf a crown
to go 'ome on.

283
00:23:02,915 --> 00:23:05,475
Well, l had a bit o' luck meself last night.

284
00:23:09,155 --> 00:23:12,511
But don't keep comin' around
countin' on 'alf crowns from me!

285
00:23:12,795 --> 00:23:15,309
Thank you, Eliza. You're a noble daughter.

286
00:23:18,435 --> 00:23:22,064
[Sings] "Beer, beer, glorious beer

287
00:23:22,715 --> 00:23:24,307
"Fill yourself right up"

288
00:23:33,715 --> 00:23:35,228
[Church bell chimes]

289
00:23:43,635 --> 00:23:46,593
HENRY'S VOlCE: See this creature
with her curbstone English...

290
00:23:46,675 --> 00:23:50,190
...that will keep her
in the gutter till the end of her days?

291
00:23:50,475 --> 00:23:54,150
In six months, I could pass her off
as a duchess at an Embassy Ball.

292
00:23:54,435 --> 00:23:57,472
I could get her ajob as a lady's maid
or a shop assistant...

293
00:23:57,555 --> 00:23:59,625
...which requires better English.

294
00:24:07,475 --> 00:24:10,911
You disgrace to the noble architecture
of these columns!

295
00:24:16,795 --> 00:24:19,593
I could get her ajob as a lady's maid
or a shop assistant...

296
00:24:19,675 --> 00:24:21,745
...which requires better English.

297
00:24:37,115 --> 00:24:38,867
[Resonating metallic clang]

298
00:24:40,315 --> 00:24:43,068
[Enunciating vowel sounds
to pitch of tuning fork]

299
00:24:47,195 --> 00:24:49,231
How many vowel sounds
did you hear altogether?

300
00:24:49,315 --> 00:24:50,953
l believe l counted 24.

301
00:24:51,075 --> 00:24:53,873
Wrong by 100. To be exact you heard 130.

302
00:24:54,595 --> 00:24:56,153
Listen to them one at a time.

303
00:24:56,235 --> 00:24:59,113
Must l? l'm really quite done up
for one morning.

304
00:24:59,955 --> 00:25:02,230
[Vowel sounds droning on phonograph]

305
00:25:22,315 --> 00:25:24,033
BUTLER: Your name, please?

306
00:25:24,355 --> 00:25:25,629
Your name, miss?

307
00:25:25,715 --> 00:25:28,513
My name is of no concern to you
whatsoever.

308
00:25:28,635 --> 00:25:30,353
BUTLER: One moment, please.

309
00:25:38,995 --> 00:25:41,509
London is gettin' so dirty these days.

310
00:25:42,075 --> 00:25:45,306
MRS. PEARCE: l'm Mrs. Pearce,
the housekeeper. Can l help you?

311
00:25:45,395 --> 00:25:48,865
Good morning, missus.
l'd like to see the professor, please.

312
00:25:48,995 --> 00:25:50,508
Could you tell me what it's about?

313
00:25:50,595 --> 00:25:53,063
lt's business of a personal nature.

314
00:25:55,235 --> 00:25:56,668
One moment, please.

315
00:26:00,115 --> 00:26:02,675
[Vowel sounds droning on phonograph]

316
00:26:05,875 --> 00:26:08,435
-Mr. Higgins?
-What is it, Mrs. Pearce?

317
00:26:08,515 --> 00:26:10,949
There's a young woman
who wants to see you, sir.

318
00:26:11,035 --> 00:26:12,184
A young woman?

319
00:26:13,315 --> 00:26:14,270
What does she want?

320
00:26:14,355 --> 00:26:16,994
She's quite a common girl, sir.
Very common indeed.

321
00:26:17,075 --> 00:26:19,031
l should've sent her away, only l thought...

322
00:26:19,115 --> 00:26:21,026
...you wanted her to talk
into your machine.

323
00:26:21,115 --> 00:26:23,788
-Has she an interesting accent?
-Simply ghastly.

324
00:26:23,875 --> 00:26:26,753
Good. Let's have her in.
Show her in, Mrs. Pearce.

325
00:26:27,515 --> 00:26:30,825
This is rather a bit of luck.
l'll show you how l make records.

326
00:26:30,915 --> 00:26:34,669
We'll set her talking, then l'll take
her down first in Bell's Visible Speech...

327
00:26:34,755 --> 00:26:37,792
...then in broad Romic.
Then we'll get her on the phonograph...

328
00:26:37,875 --> 00:26:42,107
...so you can turn her on when you want
with the written transcript before you.

329
00:26:44,635 --> 00:26:46,944
MRS. PEARCE:
This is the young woman, sir.

330
00:26:47,035 --> 00:26:48,263
Good mornin', my good man.

331
00:26:48,355 --> 00:26:50,186
Might l 'ave a word with you?

332
00:26:50,275 --> 00:26:52,664
Oh, no. This is the girl
l jotted down last night.

333
00:26:52,755 --> 00:26:55,872
She's no use. l got the records l want
of the Lisson Grove lingo.

334
00:26:55,955 --> 00:26:57,786
l won't waste another cylinder on that.

335
00:26:57,875 --> 00:26:59,433
Be off with you. l don't want you.

336
00:26:59,515 --> 00:27:02,552
Don't be so saucy.
You ain't 'eard what l come for yet.

337
00:27:02,715 --> 00:27:04,433
Did you tell 'im l come in a taxi?

338
00:27:04,515 --> 00:27:07,427
Nonsense. Do you think a gentleman
like Mr. Higgins cares...

339
00:27:07,515 --> 00:27:08,630
...what you came in?

340
00:27:08,715 --> 00:27:10,228
Oh, we are proud.

341
00:27:10,395 --> 00:27:13,512
He ain't above givin' lessons, not 'im.
l 'eard 'im say so.

342
00:27:13,595 --> 00:27:15,586
l ain't come here to ask
for any compliment...

343
00:27:15,675 --> 00:27:18,314
...and if my money's not good enough,
l can go elsewhere.

344
00:27:18,395 --> 00:27:19,794
Good enough for what?

345
00:27:19,875 --> 00:27:21,627
ELlZA: Good enough for you.

346
00:27:22,635 --> 00:27:25,354
Now you know, don't ya?
l'm come to 'ave lessons.

347
00:27:25,435 --> 00:27:27,869
And to pay for 'em, too, make no mistake.

348
00:27:27,995 --> 00:27:28,950
Well!

349
00:27:29,715 --> 00:27:32,104
And what do you expect me to say?

350
00:27:32,915 --> 00:27:36,271
Well, if you was a gentleman,
you might ask me to sit down, l think.

351
00:27:36,355 --> 00:27:38,949
Don't l tell you l'm bringin' you business?

352
00:27:39,675 --> 00:27:41,552
Should we ask this baggage to sit down...

353
00:27:41,635 --> 00:27:43,944
...or shall we just throw her
out of the window?

354
00:27:44,035 --> 00:27:48,267
l won't be called a baggage.
Not when l've offered to pay like any lady.

355
00:27:49,075 --> 00:27:51,305
PlCKERlNG: What do you want, my girl?

356
00:27:54,755 --> 00:27:56,507
l want to be a lady in a flow'r shop...

357
00:27:56,595 --> 00:27:59,314
...'stead of sellin' at the corner
of Tottenham Court Road.

358
00:27:59,395 --> 00:28:02,034
But they won't take me
unless l can talk more genteel.

359
00:28:02,115 --> 00:28:03,343
He said 'e could teach me.

360
00:28:03,435 --> 00:28:05,426
Well, 'ere l am ready to pay 'im.

361
00:28:05,515 --> 00:28:08,632
Not asking any favor
and he treats me as if l was dirt.

362
00:28:09,275 --> 00:28:12,984
l know what lessons cost as well as you do
and l'm ready to pay.

363
00:28:15,835 --> 00:28:17,109
How much?

364
00:28:17,555 --> 00:28:19,193
Now you're talkin'.

365
00:28:19,395 --> 00:28:21,829
l thought you'd come off it
for a chance to get back...

366
00:28:21,915 --> 00:28:23,951
...a bit of what you chucked
at me last night.

367
00:28:24,035 --> 00:28:25,673
You'd had a drop in, 'adn't you?

368
00:28:25,755 --> 00:28:26,904
Sit down.

369
00:28:27,035 --> 00:28:30,107
-lf you're goin' t' make a compliment of it--
-Sit down!

370
00:28:31,035 --> 00:28:33,151
Sit down, girl. Do as you're told.

371
00:28:33,675 --> 00:28:34,994
What's your name?

372
00:28:35,115 --> 00:28:36,707
Eliza Doolittle.

373
00:28:37,595 --> 00:28:39,950
Won't you sit down, Miss Doolittle?

374
00:28:43,675 --> 00:28:45,188
l don't mind if l do.

375
00:28:45,315 --> 00:28:47,067
[Pickering chuckles]

376
00:28:48,595 --> 00:28:51,587
How much do you propose
to pay me for these lessons?

377
00:28:51,795 --> 00:28:53,228
Oh, l know what's right.

378
00:28:53,315 --> 00:28:56,068
My lady friend gets French lessons
for 18 pence an hour...

379
00:28:56,155 --> 00:28:57,986
...from a real French gentleman.

380
00:28:58,075 --> 00:29:00,305
You wouldn't have the face
to ask me the same...

381
00:29:00,395 --> 00:29:03,114
...for teachin' me my own language
as you would for French.

382
00:29:03,195 --> 00:29:06,426
l won't give more than a shillin'.
Take it or leave it.

383
00:29:08,475 --> 00:29:11,433
Do you know, Pickering,
if you think of a shilling...

384
00:29:11,675 --> 00:29:15,588
...not as a simple shilling,
but as a percentage of this girl's income...

385
00:29:15,915 --> 00:29:18,509
...it works out as fully equivalent of...

386
00:29:20,155 --> 00:29:22,510
...60 or 70 pounds from a millionaire.

387
00:29:23,315 --> 00:29:26,591
By George, it's enormous.
lt's the biggest offer l ever had.

388
00:29:26,675 --> 00:29:30,714
[Yells] Sixty pounds? What are you talkin'
about? Where would l get 60 pounds?

389
00:29:30,795 --> 00:29:33,070
-l never offered you 60 pounds!
-Hold your tongue!

390
00:29:33,155 --> 00:29:34,907
[Sobs] But l ain't got 60 pounds!

391
00:29:34,995 --> 00:29:38,431
Don't cry, silly girl. Sit down.
Nobody's going to touch your money.

392
00:29:38,515 --> 00:29:41,712
Somebody'll touch you with a broomstick
if you don't stop sniveling.

393
00:29:41,795 --> 00:29:43,148
[Yells] Sit down!

394
00:29:46,715 --> 00:29:49,149
Anybody'd think you was my father!

395
00:29:49,275 --> 00:29:52,745
lf l decide to teach you,
l'll be worse than two fathers to you.

396
00:29:53,515 --> 00:29:54,470
Here.

397
00:29:54,755 --> 00:29:55,744
What's this for?

398
00:29:55,835 --> 00:29:59,464
To wipe your eyes. To wipe any part
of your face that feels moist.

399
00:29:59,675 --> 00:30:02,394
Remember, that's your handkerchief
and that's your sleeve.

400
00:30:02,475 --> 00:30:05,911
Don't confuse one with the other,
if you want to become a lady in a shop.

401
00:30:05,995 --> 00:30:09,670
lt's no use to talk to her like that.
She doesn't understand you.

402
00:30:09,755 --> 00:30:13,225
Give the 'andkerchief to me.
He give it to me, not to you!

403
00:30:13,395 --> 00:30:15,306
Higgins, l'm interested.

404
00:30:15,475 --> 00:30:16,703
What about your boast...

405
00:30:16,795 --> 00:30:19,548
...you could pass her off as a duchess
at the Embassy Ball?

406
00:30:19,635 --> 00:30:22,354
l'll say you're the greatest teacher alive
if you do that.

407
00:30:22,435 --> 00:30:25,984
l'll bet you all the expenses
of the experiment that you can't do it.

408
00:30:26,075 --> 00:30:28,225
I'll even pay for the lessons.

409
00:30:28,315 --> 00:30:30,829
You're real good. Thank ye, Capt'n.

410
00:30:32,275 --> 00:30:34,152
lt's almost irresistible.

411
00:30:34,435 --> 00:30:36,027
[Henry chuckles]

412
00:30:36,755 --> 00:30:38,746
She's so deliciously low.

413
00:30:39,035 --> 00:30:40,514
So horribly dirty.

414
00:30:40,635 --> 00:30:44,025
l ain't dirty! l washed my face an' hands
before l come, l did.

415
00:30:44,115 --> 00:30:47,903
l'll take it. l'll make a duchess
of this draggle-tailed guttersnipe.

416
00:30:48,275 --> 00:30:51,665
We'll start today. This moment.
Take her away and clean her.

417
00:30:51,755 --> 00:30:55,031
Sandpaper, if it won't come off.
ls there a fire in the kitchen?

418
00:30:55,115 --> 00:30:58,027
Take her clothes off and burn them
and order some new ones.

419
00:30:58,115 --> 00:31:00,629
Just wrap her in brown paper
till they come.

420
00:31:01,115 --> 00:31:04,551
You're no gentleman, you're not,
to talk o' such things.

421
00:31:04,635 --> 00:31:06,068
l'm a good girl, l am.

422
00:31:06,155 --> 00:31:08,828
And l know what the likes of you are, l do.

423
00:31:09,475 --> 00:31:12,547
We want none of your slum prudery here,
young woman.

424
00:31:12,795 --> 00:31:14,945
You've got to learn to behave
like a duchess.

425
00:31:15,035 --> 00:31:18,345
Take her away, Mrs. Pearce.
lf she gives you any trouble, wallop her.

426
00:31:18,435 --> 00:31:20,187
l'll call the police, l will.

427
00:31:20,275 --> 00:31:21,833
l've got no place to put her.

428
00:31:21,915 --> 00:31:23,633
Well, put her in the dustbin.

429
00:31:23,715 --> 00:31:24,625
[Eliza shrieks]

430
00:31:24,835 --> 00:31:26,632
Come, Higgins, be reasonable.

431
00:31:26,715 --> 00:31:29,183
You must be reasonable,
Mr. Higgins, you must.

432
00:31:29,275 --> 00:31:31,664
You can't walk over everybody like this.

433
00:31:34,315 --> 00:31:35,304
l?

434
00:31:36,075 --> 00:31:37,793
Walk over everybody?

435
00:31:37,875 --> 00:31:41,868
My dear Mrs. Pearce, my dear Pickering,
l had no intention of walking over anybody.

436
00:31:41,955 --> 00:31:44,992
l merely suggested we should be kind
to this poor girl.

437
00:31:45,115 --> 00:31:49,472
l didn't express myself clearly
because l didn't wish to hurt her delicacy...

438
00:31:49,875 --> 00:31:50,944
...or yours.

439
00:31:51,035 --> 00:31:53,993
But, sir, you can't take a girl up like that...

440
00:31:54,155 --> 00:31:56,669
...as if you were picking up
a pebble on the beach.

441
00:31:56,755 --> 00:31:57,870
Why not?

442
00:31:58,035 --> 00:32:00,708
Why not? But you don't know
anything about her.

443
00:32:00,795 --> 00:32:03,468
What about her parents?
She may be married.

444
00:32:03,675 --> 00:32:04,790
Garn!

445
00:32:05,195 --> 00:32:08,153
There. As the girl
very properly says, "garn! "

446
00:32:08,915 --> 00:32:10,428
Who'd marry me?

447
00:32:12,835 --> 00:32:14,553
By George, Eliza...

448
00:32:15,315 --> 00:32:18,591
...the streets will be strewn
with the bodies of men...

449
00:32:18,755 --> 00:32:22,191
...shooting themselves for your sake
before l'm done with you.

450
00:32:24,715 --> 00:32:25,830
l'm goin'.

451
00:32:26,115 --> 00:32:29,505
He's off his chump, he is.
l don't want no balmies teachin' me.

452
00:32:29,595 --> 00:32:32,632
Mad? All right, Mrs. Pearce,
don't order those new clothes.

453
00:32:32,715 --> 00:32:34,831
-Throw her out.
-Stop! l won't allow it.

454
00:32:34,915 --> 00:32:36,348
Go home to your parents, girl.

455
00:32:36,435 --> 00:32:38,107
l ain't got no parents.

456
00:32:38,315 --> 00:32:40,146
She ain't got no parents. What's the fuss?

457
00:32:40,235 --> 00:32:43,432
Nobody wants her. She's no use
to anyone but me. Take her upstairs!

458
00:32:43,515 --> 00:32:46,427
MRS. PEARCE: What's to become of her?
ls she to be paid anything?

459
00:32:46,515 --> 00:32:47,743
Do be sensible, sir.

460
00:32:47,835 --> 00:32:50,224
What'd she do with money?
She'll have food and clothes.

461
00:32:50,315 --> 00:32:51,828
She'll drink if you give her money.

462
00:32:51,915 --> 00:32:53,587
You are a brute! lt's a lie!

463
00:32:53,675 --> 00:32:56,064
Nobody ever saw the sign o' liquor on me.

464
00:32:56,155 --> 00:32:59,113
Sir, you're a gentleman.
Don't let 'im speak to me like that!

465
00:32:59,195 --> 00:33:02,267
Does it occur to you, Higgins,
the girl has some feelings?

466
00:33:02,355 --> 00:33:05,347
No, l don't think so.
No feelings we need worry about.

467
00:33:05,555 --> 00:33:06,590
Well, have you, Eliza?

468
00:33:06,675 --> 00:33:08,905
l got me feelings same as anyone else.

469
00:33:08,995 --> 00:33:12,146
Mr. Higgins, l must know on what terms
the girl is to be here.

470
