750
00:49:06,035 --> 00:49:07,946
[Continues enunciating vowels]

751
00:49:09,915 --> 00:49:12,349
[Droning sound of Eliza repeating vowels]

752
00:49:42,235 --> 00:49:44,226
[Shouting vowel sounds]

753
00:49:45,475 --> 00:49:47,909
You simply cannot go on
working the girl this way.

754
00:49:47,995 --> 00:49:50,190
Making her say her alphabet
over and over...

755
00:49:50,275 --> 00:49:52,914
...from sunup to sundown,
even during meals.

756
00:49:53,075 --> 00:49:55,543
You'll exhaust yourself. When will it stop?

757
00:49:55,635 --> 00:49:59,071
When she does it properly, of course.
ls that all, Mrs. Pearce?

758
00:49:59,155 --> 00:50:02,511
There's another letter from the
American millionaire, Ezra D. Wallingford.

759
00:50:02,595 --> 00:50:04,711
He still wants you
for his Moral Reform League.

760
00:50:04,795 --> 00:50:05,830
Throw it away.

761
00:50:05,915 --> 00:50:09,271
lt's the third letter he's written you.
You should at least answer it.

762
00:50:09,355 --> 00:50:13,109
All right, leave it on the desk, Mrs. Pearce.
l'll try and get to it.

763
00:50:15,195 --> 00:50:19,108
BUTLER: lf you please, sir. There's
a dustman downstairs, Alfred P. Doolittle...

764
00:50:19,195 --> 00:50:22,073
...who wants to see you.
He says you have his daughter here.

765
00:50:22,155 --> 00:50:23,304
l say!

766
00:50:24,515 --> 00:50:26,187
Well, send the blackguard up.

767
00:50:26,275 --> 00:50:28,470
PlCKERlNG: He may not be
a blackguard, Higgins.

768
00:50:28,555 --> 00:50:31,023
Nonsense. Of course
he's a blackguard, Pickering.

769
00:50:31,115 --> 00:50:33,390
l'm afraid we'll have some trouble
with him.

770
00:50:33,475 --> 00:50:37,787
No, l think not. Any trouble to be had,
he'll have it with me. Not l with him.

771
00:50:40,915 --> 00:50:42,268
Doolittle, sir.

772
00:50:48,435 --> 00:50:51,074
ALFlE: Professor Higgins?
HENRY: [Shouts] Here!

773
00:50:51,555 --> 00:50:52,544
Where?

774
00:50:53,075 --> 00:50:54,872
Good morning, Governor.

775
00:50:55,275 --> 00:50:58,187
l come about a very serious matter,
Governor.

776
00:51:01,555 --> 00:51:03,511
Brought up in Houndslow.

777
00:51:04,155 --> 00:51:06,032
Mother Welsh, l should think.

778
00:51:06,995 --> 00:51:08,508
What is it you want, Doolittle?

779
00:51:08,595 --> 00:51:11,029
l want my daughter, that's what l want.
See?

780
00:51:11,115 --> 00:51:13,504
Of course you do.
You're her father, aren't you?

781
00:51:13,595 --> 00:51:16,109
l'm glad to see you have a spark
of family feeling left.

782
00:51:16,195 --> 00:51:18,709
She's in there. Yes, take her away at once.

783
00:51:18,875 --> 00:51:19,864
What?

784
00:51:20,395 --> 00:51:24,183
Take her away. Do you think l am going
to keep your daughter for you?

785
00:51:24,315 --> 00:51:26,749
Now, is this reasonable, Governor?

786
00:51:27,115 --> 00:51:30,027
ls it fairity to take advantage
of a man like that?

787
00:51:30,195 --> 00:51:33,312
The girl belongs to me. You got 'er.
Where do l come in?

788
00:51:33,755 --> 00:51:37,031
How dare you come here
and attempt to blackmail me!

789
00:51:37,835 --> 00:51:39,712
You sent her here on purpose!

790
00:51:39,835 --> 00:51:42,588
Don't take a man up like that, Governor.

791
00:51:43,155 --> 00:51:45,225
The police shall take you up.
This is a plan...

792
00:51:45,315 --> 00:51:47,590
...a plot to extort money by threats.

793
00:51:47,675 --> 00:51:49,552
l shall telephone the police.

794
00:51:49,675 --> 00:51:52,314
Have l asked you for a brass farthin'?

795
00:51:53,035 --> 00:51:56,471
l leave it to this gentleman 'ere.
Have l said a word about money?

796
00:51:56,555 --> 00:51:58,625
Well, what else did you come for?

797
00:52:00,435 --> 00:52:02,346
What would a bloke come for?

798
00:52:02,715 --> 00:52:04,433
Be 'uman, Governor.

799
00:52:04,715 --> 00:52:06,228
[Alfie cackles]

800
00:52:09,435 --> 00:52:12,029
Alfred, you sent her here on purpose.

801
00:52:12,395 --> 00:52:13,987
So help me, Governor, l never did.

802
00:52:14,075 --> 00:52:15,428
How did you know she was here?

803
00:52:15,515 --> 00:52:18,268
l'd tell you, Governor,
if you'd let me get a word in.

804
00:52:18,355 --> 00:52:21,108
l'm willing to tell ya.
l'm wanting to tell ya.

805
00:52:21,355 --> 00:52:23,073
l'm waiting to tell ya!

806
00:52:24,715 --> 00:52:28,594
You know, Pickering, this chap's got
a certain natural gift of rhetoric.

807
00:52:28,795 --> 00:52:31,593
Observe the rhythm
of his native woodnotes wild.

808
00:52:31,835 --> 00:52:35,623
"l'm willing to tell you. l'm wanting
to tell you. l'm waiting to tell you."

809
00:52:35,715 --> 00:52:37,785
That's the Welsh strain in 'im.

810
00:52:38,035 --> 00:52:40,549
How did you know Eliza was here
if you didn't send her?

811
00:52:40,635 --> 00:52:43,991
Well, she sent back for her luggage
and l got to 'ear about it.

812
00:52:44,075 --> 00:52:46,589
She said she didn't want no clothes.

813
00:52:47,275 --> 00:52:51,746
What was l to think from that, Governor?
l ask you, as a parent, what was l to think?

814
00:52:52,195 --> 00:52:55,790
So you came here to rescue her
from worse than death, eh?

815
00:52:56,115 --> 00:52:58,504
-Yes, sir, Governor. That's right.
-Yes.

816
00:52:58,875 --> 00:53:00,228
Mrs. Pearce!

817
00:53:01,595 --> 00:53:04,905
Eliza's father has come to take her away.
Give her to him, will you?

818
00:53:04,995 --> 00:53:08,271
ALFlE: Now wait a minute, Governor.
Wait a minute.

819
00:53:09,195 --> 00:53:11,755
You and me is men o' the world, ain't we?

820
00:53:12,235 --> 00:53:16,148
Men of the world, are we?
Perhaps you'd better go, Mrs. Pearce.

821
00:53:16,235 --> 00:53:17,873
l think so indeed, sir!

822
00:53:18,275 --> 00:53:19,833
ALFlE: Here, Governor.

823
00:53:19,915 --> 00:53:22,713
l've took a sort of a fancy to you and...

824
00:53:25,915 --> 00:53:29,146
...if you want the girl, l ain't so set
on 'avin' her home again...

825
00:53:29,235 --> 00:53:32,033
...but what l might be open to
is an arrangement.

826
00:53:32,435 --> 00:53:34,744
All l ask is my rights as a father.

827
00:53:34,835 --> 00:53:38,350
You're the last man alive to expect me
to let her go for nothing.

828
00:53:38,675 --> 00:53:41,553
l can see you're a straight sort, Governor.

829
00:53:41,875 --> 00:53:42,864
So...

830
00:53:43,115 --> 00:53:46,744
...what's a five pound note to you?
An' what's Eliza to me?

831
00:53:47,355 --> 00:53:48,993
l think you should know, Doolittle...

832
00:53:49,075 --> 00:53:52,112
...that Mr. Higgins' intentions
are entirely honorable.

833
00:53:52,475 --> 00:53:56,150
Of course they are, Governor.
lf l thought they wasn't, l'd ask 50.

834
00:53:56,635 --> 00:53:59,354
You mean, you'd sell your daughter
for 50 pounds?

835
00:53:59,435 --> 00:54:01,107
Have you no morals, man?

836
00:54:03,995 --> 00:54:07,908
No, l can't afford 'em, Governor. Neither
could you if you was as poor as me.

837
00:54:07,995 --> 00:54:10,111
Not that l mean any 'arm, but...

838
00:54:10,195 --> 00:54:13,551
...if Eliza is gonna have a bit out o' this,
why not me, too?

839
00:54:14,795 --> 00:54:15,830
Why not?

840
00:54:18,635 --> 00:54:20,865
Look at it my way. What am l?

841
00:54:21,995 --> 00:54:25,908
l ask ya, what am l? l'm one
o' the undeserving poor, that's what l am.

842
00:54:25,995 --> 00:54:27,951
Think what that means to a man.

843
00:54:28,035 --> 00:54:31,584
lt means he's up against
middle-class morality for all the time.

844
00:54:32,155 --> 00:54:35,943
lf there's anything goin' an' l ask
for a bit of it, it's always the same story:

845
00:54:36,035 --> 00:54:38,549
"You're undeservin', so you can't have it."

846
00:54:38,715 --> 00:54:42,549
But my needs is as great as the most
deservin' widows that ever got money...

847
00:54:42,635 --> 00:54:46,947
...out of six different charities in one week
for the death o' the same 'usband.

848
00:54:47,035 --> 00:54:50,345
l don't need less than a deservin' man,
l need more.

849
00:54:50,835 --> 00:54:53,713
l don't eat less 'earty than he does
and l drink...

850
00:54:54,475 --> 00:54:55,669
...a lot more.

851
00:54:55,955 --> 00:54:57,866
l'm playin' straight with you.

852
00:54:57,955 --> 00:55:01,504
l ain't pretendin' to be deservin'.
No, l'm undeservin'...

853
00:55:01,995 --> 00:55:05,874
...and l mean to go on bein' undeservin'.
l like it an' that's the truth.

854
00:55:05,955 --> 00:55:09,072
But will you take advantage
of a man's nature...

855
00:55:09,635 --> 00:55:12,945
...do him out of the price of
his own daughter, what he's brought up...

856
00:55:13,035 --> 00:55:15,629
...fed and clothed
by the sweat of his brow...

857
00:55:16,315 --> 00:55:20,627
...till she's growed big enough
to be interestin' to you two gentlemen?

858
00:55:22,635 --> 00:55:25,593
ls five pounds unreasonable,
l put it to you?

859
00:55:26,195 --> 00:55:27,753
And l leave it to you.

860
00:55:30,475 --> 00:55:33,911
You know, Pickering, if we took this man
in hand for three months...

861
00:55:33,995 --> 00:55:38,227
...he could choose between a seat in
the Cabinet and a popular pulpit in Wales.

862
00:55:38,635 --> 00:55:42,025
-We'd better give 'im a fiver.
-He'll make bad use of it, l'm afraid.

863
00:55:42,115 --> 00:55:44,265
ALFlE: Not me, Governor,
so 'elp me l won't.

864
00:55:44,355 --> 00:55:46,744
Just one good spree
for meself an' the missus...

865
00:55:46,835 --> 00:55:49,793
...givin' pleasure to ourselves
and employment to others.

866
00:55:49,875 --> 00:55:52,628
An' satisfaction to you to know
it ain't been throwed away.

867
00:55:52,715 --> 00:55:54,592
ALFlE: You couldn't spend it better.

868
00:55:54,675 --> 00:55:57,314
This is irresistible. Let's give 'im ten.

869
00:55:57,395 --> 00:55:59,511
The missus wouldn't have the 'eart
to spend ten.

870
00:55:59,595 --> 00:56:01,233
Ten pounds is a lot o' money.

871
00:56:01,315 --> 00:56:04,705
Makes a man feel prudent-like,
and then goodbye to 'appiness.

872
00:56:05,115 --> 00:56:08,994
No, you just give me what l ask, Governor.
Not a penny less, not a penny more.

873
00:56:09,075 --> 00:56:12,272
l rather draw the line at encouraging
this sort of immorality.

874
00:56:12,355 --> 00:56:14,346
Why don't you marry that missus of yours?

875
00:56:14,435 --> 00:56:17,711
After all, marriage isn't so frightening.
You married Eliza's mother.

876
00:56:17,795 --> 00:56:19,353
Who told you that, Governor?

877
00:56:19,435 --> 00:56:22,154
Well, nobody told me.
l concluded, naturally....

878
00:56:25,915 --> 00:56:29,305
lf we listen to this man for another minute
we'll have no convictions left.

879
00:56:29,395 --> 00:56:32,114
-Five pounds, l think you said.
-Thank you, Governor.

880
00:56:32,195 --> 00:56:33,514
Are you sure you won't have ten?

881
00:56:33,595 --> 00:56:35,586
No. No, perhaps another time.

882
00:56:35,675 --> 00:56:37,586
ELlZA: [Shrieks] l won't, l won't!

883
00:56:37,675 --> 00:56:38,869
l beg your pardon, miss.

884
00:56:38,955 --> 00:56:41,594
l won't say those ruddy vowels
one more time.

885
00:56:41,675 --> 00:56:43,267
Blimey, it's Eliza.

886
00:56:43,355 --> 00:56:46,028
ALFlE: l never thought she'd clean up
so good-looking.

887
00:56:46,115 --> 00:56:48,026
She does me credit, don't she?

888
00:56:48,115 --> 00:56:50,071
What are you doin' here?

889
00:56:50,635 --> 00:56:54,913
Now, you hold your tongue and don't
you give these gentlemen none o' your lip.

890
00:56:55,435 --> 00:56:58,632
lf you have any trouble with 'er,
give 'er a few licks o' the strap.

891
00:56:58,715 --> 00:57:00,910
That's the way to improve 'er mind.

892
00:57:01,195 --> 00:57:03,789
Well, good morning, gentlemen.
Cheerio, Eliza.

893
00:57:07,315 --> 00:57:10,864
There's a man for you.
A philosophical genius of the first water.

894
00:57:11,995 --> 00:57:14,555
HENRY: Write to Mr. Ezra Wallingford
and tell him...

895
00:57:14,635 --> 00:57:17,832
...if he wants a lecturer, to get in touch
with Mr. Doolittle...

896
00:57:17,915 --> 00:57:21,544
...a common dustman, one of
the most original moralists in England.

897
00:57:21,835 --> 00:57:23,427
What did he come for?

898
00:57:23,795 --> 00:57:24,784
Say your vowels.

899
00:57:24,875 --> 00:57:26,831
l know me vowels.
l knew 'em before l come.

900
00:57:26,915 --> 00:57:28,143
lf you know them, say them.

901
00:57:28,235 --> 00:57:30,191
Ahyee, e, iyee, ow, you.

902
00:57:32,155 --> 00:57:33,634
A, E, l, O, U.

903
00:57:34,755 --> 00:57:37,553
That's what l said. Ahyee, e, iyee, ow, you.

904
00:57:37,635 --> 00:57:40,354
That's what l've said for three days
an' l won't no more.

905
00:57:40,435 --> 00:57:43,427
l know it's difficult, Miss Doolittle,
but try to understand.

906
00:57:43,515 --> 00:57:46,587
There's no use explaining.
As a military man you should know that.

907
00:57:46,675 --> 00:57:48,154
Drilling is what she needs.

908
00:57:48,235 --> 00:57:50,544
Leave her alone or she'll turn to you
for sympathy.

909
00:57:50,635 --> 00:57:53,547
Very well, if you insist,
but have a little patience with her.

910
00:57:53,635 --> 00:57:54,784
Of course.

911
00:57:55,395 --> 00:57:56,623
Say "A."

912
00:57:56,875 --> 00:57:58,945
You ain't got no 'eart, you ain't.

913
00:57:59,235 --> 00:58:01,703
[Henry utters vowel sounds, Eliza repeats]

914
00:58:06,155 --> 00:58:10,034
l promise you, you'll say your vowels
correctly before this day is out...

915
00:58:10,315 --> 00:58:13,910
...or there'll be no lunch,
no dinner, and no chocolates.

916
