01:34:11,395 --> 01:34:14,785
Higgins, l'm trying to tell you
that l want to call off the bet.

1422
01:34:14,875 --> 01:34:17,025
l know you're a stubborn man, but so am l.

1423
01:34:17,115 --> 01:34:18,946
This experiment is over.

1424
01:34:19,035 --> 01:34:23,187
And nothing short of an order
from the king could force me to recant.

1425
01:34:23,635 --> 01:34:24,704
Excuse me.

1426
01:34:25,115 --> 01:34:27,390
You understand, Higgins? lt's over.

1427
01:34:29,075 --> 01:34:31,748
Higgins, if there's any mishap
at the Embassy tonight...

1428
01:34:31,835 --> 01:34:34,349
...if Miss Doolittle suffers
any embarrassment...

1429
01:34:34,435 --> 01:34:35,629
...it'll be on your head alone.

1430
01:34:35,715 --> 01:34:36,909
HENRY: Eliza can do anything.

1431
01:34:36,995 --> 01:34:38,713
Suppose she's discovered?
Remember Ascot.

1432
01:34:38,795 --> 01:34:40,592
Suppose she makes
another ghastly mistake?

1433
01:34:40,675 --> 01:34:43,235
There'll be no horses at the ball, Pickering.

1434
01:34:45,195 --> 01:34:47,390
PlCKERlNG: Think of how agonizing
it would be.

1435
01:34:47,475 --> 01:34:50,035
lf anything happened tonight,
l don't know what l'd do.

1436
01:34:50,115 --> 01:34:51,628
You could always rejoin your regiment.

1437
01:34:51,715 --> 01:34:53,467
This is no time for flippancy, Higgins.

1438
01:34:53,555 --> 01:34:55,511
The way you've driven her
the last six weeks...

1439
01:34:55,595 --> 01:34:57,586
...has exceeded all bounds
of common decency.

1440
01:34:57,675 --> 01:35:00,553
For God's sake, stop pacing.
Can't you settle somewhere?

1441
01:35:00,635 --> 01:35:02,512
Have some port. lt'll quieten your nerves.

1442
01:35:02,595 --> 01:35:03,869
l'm not nervous.

1443
01:35:05,435 --> 01:35:07,266
-Where is it?
-On the piano.

1444
01:35:08,755 --> 01:35:10,029
The car's here, sir.

1445
01:35:10,115 --> 01:35:11,707
Good. Tell Miss Doolittle.

1446
01:35:11,795 --> 01:35:15,265
Tell Miss Doolittle indeed.
l'll bet you that damned gown doesn't fit.

1447
01:35:15,355 --> 01:35:17,346
l warned you about these French designers.

1448
01:35:17,435 --> 01:35:20,632
We should've gone to an English shop.
They would've been on our side.

1449
01:35:20,715 --> 01:35:22,945
-Have a glass of port?
-No, thank you.

1450
01:35:29,035 --> 01:35:33,074
Are you so sure this girl will retain
everything you've hammered into her?

1451
01:35:33,635 --> 01:35:35,227
Well, we shall see.

1452
01:35:35,355 --> 01:35:37,425
PlCKERlNG: Suppose she doesn't?

1453
01:35:38,235 --> 01:35:39,304
l lose my bet.

1454
01:35:39,395 --> 01:35:43,388
PlCKERlNG: There's one thing l can't stand
about you, your confounded complacency.

1455
01:35:43,475 --> 01:35:45,431
At a moment like this,
with so much at stake...

1456
01:35:45,515 --> 01:35:48,871
...it's utterly indecent
that you don't need a glass of port.

1457
01:35:50,475 --> 01:35:54,070
And what about the girl? You act
as though she doesn't matter at all.

1458
01:35:54,155 --> 01:35:56,669
Rubbish, Pickering. Of course she matters.

1459
01:35:57,035 --> 01:35:59,344
What do you think l've been doing
all these months?

1460
01:35:59,435 --> 01:36:02,791
What could possibly matter more
than to take a human being...

1461
01:36:02,875 --> 01:36:06,914
...and change her into a different human
being by creating a new speech for her?

1462
01:36:06,995 --> 01:36:10,670
lt's filling up the deepest gap
that separates class from class...

1463
01:36:10,755 --> 01:36:12,268
...and soul from soul.

1464
01:36:12,675 --> 01:36:14,711
Oh, she matters immensely.

1465
01:36:21,435 --> 01:36:23,426
[Sentimental instrumental music]

1466
01:36:36,435 --> 01:36:38,824
Miss Doolittle, you look beautiful.

1467
01:36:39,475 --> 01:36:40,988
Thank you, Colonel Pickering.

1468
01:36:41,075 --> 01:36:42,906
Don't you think so, Higgins?

1469
01:36:45,515 --> 01:36:47,824
HENRY: Not bad. Not bad at all.

1470
01:39:22,274 --> 01:39:24,344
[Butler announcing names of guests]

1471
01:39:41,354 --> 01:39:43,026
Maestro! Maestro!

1472
01:39:45,874 --> 01:39:46,989
Don't you remember me?

1473
01:39:47,074 --> 01:39:48,632
No. Who the devil are you?

1474
01:39:48,714 --> 01:39:52,024
l'm your pupil. Your first, your greatest,
your best pupil.

1475
01:39:52,154 --> 01:39:54,543
l'm Zoltan Karpathy, that marvelous boy.

1476
01:39:55,674 --> 01:39:57,551
l made your name famous
throughout Europe.

1477
01:39:57,634 --> 01:39:59,465
You teach me phonetics.
You can't forget me.

1478
01:39:59,554 --> 01:40:01,226
Why don't you have your hair cut?

1479
01:40:01,314 --> 01:40:04,704
l don't have your imposing appearance,
your figure, your brow.

1480
01:40:04,834 --> 01:40:06,790
lf l had my hair cut,
nobody would notice me.

1481
01:40:06,874 --> 01:40:08,751
HENRY: Where did you get these old coins?

1482
01:40:08,834 --> 01:40:10,426
These are decorations for languages.

1483
01:40:10,514 --> 01:40:12,391
ZOLTAN: The Queen
of Transylvania is here.

1484
01:40:12,474 --> 01:40:15,466
l'm indispensable to her
at these official international parties.

1485
01:40:15,554 --> 01:40:18,352
l speak 32 languages.
l know everyone in Europe.

1486
01:40:18,434 --> 01:40:20,425
No imposter can escape my detection.

1487
01:40:20,514 --> 01:40:22,744
GREEK AMBASSADOR: Professor Karpathy.

1488
01:40:24,514 --> 01:40:25,993
The Greek ambassador.

1489
01:40:26,754 --> 01:40:27,789
Greek, my foot!

1490
01:40:27,874 --> 01:40:30,547
He pretends not to know English,
but he can't deceive me.

1491
01:40:30,634 --> 01:40:32,943
He's the son of a Yorkshire watchmaker.

1492
01:40:33,634 --> 01:40:36,910
He speaks English so villainously
that he cannot utter a word...

1493
01:40:36,994 --> 01:40:39,144
...without betraying his origin.

1494
01:40:39,234 --> 01:40:42,829
l help him pretend, but make him pay
through the nose. l make them all pay.

1495
01:40:42,914 --> 01:40:46,065
Excuse me, sir, you are wanted upstairs.
Her Excellency asked for you.

1496
01:41:04,994 --> 01:41:07,303
BUTLER: Viscount and Viscountess Saxon.

1497
01:41:10,154 --> 01:41:12,463
Baron and Baroness of Yorkshire.

1498
01:41:14,554 --> 01:41:16,829
Sir Guy and Lady Scot-Auckland.

1499
01:41:36,314 --> 01:41:38,384
The Count and Countess Demereau.

1500
01:41:39,074 --> 01:41:41,463
The Viscount and Viscountess Hillyard.

1501
01:41:41,634 --> 01:41:43,784
Mr. and Mrs. Richard Lanser.

1502
01:41:44,994 --> 01:41:46,905
Lord and Lady Clanders.

1503
01:41:48,154 --> 01:41:50,907
Miss Eliza Doolittle, Colonel Pickering.

1504
01:41:51,234 --> 01:41:54,032
Miss Eliza Doolittle. Colonel Pickering.

1505
01:41:55,074 --> 01:41:56,746
BUTLER: Professor Higgins.

1506
01:41:57,474 --> 01:41:59,465
-Your Excellency.
-Miss Doolittle.

1507
01:41:59,554 --> 01:42:00,782
How do you do?

1508
01:42:00,874 --> 01:42:03,069
-Good evening, Colonel.
-Good evening.

1509
01:42:04,034 --> 01:42:07,822
AMBASSADOR'S WlFE: What an enchanting
young lady you have with you this evening.

1510
01:42:07,914 --> 01:42:09,267
Well, who is she?

1511
01:42:09,434 --> 01:42:12,426
Oh, a cousin of mine. And Higgins.
Excuse me.

1512
01:42:13,314 --> 01:42:14,588
Professor Higgins.

1513
01:42:14,674 --> 01:42:18,303
Such a faraway look,
as if she's always lived in a garden.

1514
01:42:18,914 --> 01:42:20,984
So she has. A sort of garden.

1515
01:42:48,674 --> 01:42:51,984
Henry must take Eliza home at once.
There's a language expert here.

1516
01:42:52,074 --> 01:42:55,111
-Sort of, you know, "imposterologist."
-l beg you pardon?

1517
01:42:55,834 --> 01:42:58,268
The young lady with Colonel Pickering....

1518
01:42:58,394 --> 01:42:59,907
Find out who she is.

1519
01:43:00,154 --> 01:43:01,348
With pleasure.

1520
01:43:01,794 --> 01:43:04,183
The whole situation is highly explosive.

1521
01:43:09,754 --> 01:43:12,222
Tell me, Zoltan,
some more about the Greek ambassador.

1522
01:43:12,314 --> 01:43:15,750
Gladly, but first l would love you
to present me to this glorious creature.

1523
01:43:15,834 --> 01:43:17,950
Does he really come from Yorkshire?

1524
01:43:20,874 --> 01:43:23,104
[Stately instrumental prelude]

1525
01:43:26,434 --> 01:43:29,153
BUTLER: Her Majesty,
the Queen of Transylvania...

1526
01:43:29,434 --> 01:43:32,187
...and His Royal Highness Prince Gregor.

1527
01:43:35,274 --> 01:43:38,744
[Majestic march music]

1528
01:44:16,674 --> 01:44:18,710
Charming. Quite charming.

1529
01:44:20,354 --> 01:44:22,072
Miss Doolittle, Madam.

1530
01:44:53,274 --> 01:44:55,504
[Scattered, incoherent conversations]

1531
01:45:54,234 --> 01:45:57,146
Miss Doolittle, my son would like
to dance with you.

1532
01:46:12,074 --> 01:46:14,110
[lnstrumental waltz music]

1533
01:46:50,074 --> 01:46:51,223
Eliza?

1534
01:48:17,074 --> 01:48:18,712
[lncoherent whispering]

1535
01:48:52,434 --> 01:48:53,913
[Henry laughs]

1536
01:48:56,154 --> 01:48:58,145
PlCKERlNG: Absolutely fantastic.

1537
01:49:01,234 --> 01:49:02,633
HENRY: A lot of tomfoolery.

1538
01:49:02,714 --> 01:49:04,864
PlCKERlNG:
lt was an immense achievement.

1539
01:49:04,954 --> 01:49:06,353
Well, Mr. Higgins?

1540
01:49:06,594 --> 01:49:09,392
A triumph, Mrs. Pearce. A total triumph.

1541
01:49:09,874 --> 01:49:12,752
Higgins, you were superb,
absolutely superb.

1542
01:49:13,394 --> 01:49:17,182
Tell us the truth now, weren't you
a little bit nervous once or twice?

1543
01:49:17,314 --> 01:49:18,986
Not during the whole evening?

1544
01:49:19,074 --> 01:49:20,666
Not when l saw we were going to win.

1545
01:49:20,754 --> 01:49:22,665
l felt like a bear in a cage hanging about.

1546
01:49:22,754 --> 01:49:24,346
lt was an immense achievement.

1547
01:49:24,434 --> 01:49:27,392
lf l hadn't backed myself to do it,
l'd have given up two months ago.

1548
01:49:27,474 --> 01:49:28,748
Absolutely fantastic.

1549
01:49:28,834 --> 01:49:30,313
Yes, a lot of tomfoolery.

1550
01:49:30,394 --> 01:49:32,225
Higgins, l salute you.

1551
01:49:32,354 --> 01:49:34,993
The silly people don't know
their own silly business.

1552
01:49:35,074 --> 01:49:38,032
[Sings] "Tonight, old man, you did it
You did it, you did it

1553
01:49:38,114 --> 01:49:40,867
"You said that you would do it
And indeed you did

1554
01:49:40,954 --> 01:49:43,832
"l thought that you would rue it
l doubted you'd do it

1555
01:49:43,914 --> 01:49:46,747
"But now l must admit it
That succeed you did

1556
01:49:46,954 --> 01:49:49,468
"You should get a medal
Or be even made a knight

1557
01:49:49,554 --> 01:49:52,022
"Oh, it was nothing, really nothing

1558
01:49:52,794 --> 01:49:55,433
"All alone you hurdled
Every obstacle in sight

1559
01:49:55,674 --> 01:49:58,666
"Now wait, now wait
Give credit where it's due

1560
01:49:58,834 --> 01:50:01,109
"A lot of the glory goes to you

1561
01:50:01,914 --> 01:50:04,826
"But you're the one who did it
Who did it, who did it

1562
01:50:04,914 --> 01:50:07,712
"As sturdy as Gibraltar
Not a second did you falter

1563
01:50:07,794 --> 01:50:09,022
"There's no doubt about it

1564
01:50:09,114 --> 01:50:12,311
"You did it!

1565
01:50:15,354 --> 01:50:19,313
"l must have aged a year tonight
At times l thought l'd die of fright

1566
01:50:19,554 --> 01:50:21,943
"Never was there a momentary lull

1567
01:50:23,274 --> 01:50:26,744
"Shortly after we came in
l saw at once we'd easily win

1568
01:50:27,234 --> 01:50:29,873
"And after that l found it deadly dull

1569
01:50:30,514 --> 01:50:33,233
PlCKERlNG: "You should have heard
The 'oohs' and 'aahs'

1570
01:50:33,314 --> 01:50:35,225
"Everyone wondering who she was

1571
01:50:35,314 --> 01:50:37,874
"You'd think they'd never seen
a lady before

1572
01:50:38,554 --> 01:50:41,990
"And when the Prince of Transylvania
Asked to meet her

1573
01:50:43,634 --> 01:50:46,467
"And gave his arm to lead her to the floor

1574
01:50:48,474 --> 01:50:51,625
"l said to him: 'You did it
You did it, you did it'

1575
01:50:51,714 --> 01:50:54,751
"They thought she was ecstatic
And so damned aristocratic

1576
01:50:54,834 --> 01:50:57,109
"And they never knew
That you...

1577
01:50:59,154 --> 01:51:00,269
"...did it"

1578
01:51:02,394 --> 01:51:04,191
Thank goodness for Zoltan Karpathy.

1579
01:51:04,274 --> 01:51:06,424
lf it hadn't been for him
l would've died of boredom.

1580
01:51:06,514 --> 01:51:08,664
Karpathy? That dreadful Hungarian?
Was he there?

1581
01:51:08,754 --> 01:51:11,632
Yes, he was there all right
and up to his old tricks.

1582
01:51:11,714 --> 01:51:14,467
[Sings] "That blackguard
Who uses the science of speech

1583
01:51:14,554 --> 01:51:16,988
"More to blackmail and swindle than teach

1584
01:51:17,354 --> 01:51:19,743
"He made it the devilish business of his

1585
01:51:20,034 --> 01:51:22,707
"To find out who this Miss Doolittle is

1586
01:51:23,874 --> 01:51:26,229
"Every time we looked around
There he was

1587
01:51:26,354 --> 01:51:28,424
"That hairy hound from Budapest

1588
01:51:30,354 --> 01:51:33,232
"Never leaving us alone
Never have l ever known

1589
01:51:33,314 --> 01:51:34,542
"A ruder pest

1590
01:51:36,434 --> 01:51:40,507
"Finally l decided it was foolish
Not to let him have his chance with her

1591
01:51:42,474 --> 01:51:45,466
"So l stepped aside
And let him dance with her

1592
01:51:47,994 --> 01:51:52,909
"Oozing charm from every pore
He oiled his way around the floor

1593
01:51:53,234 --> 01:51:57,068
"Every trick that he could play
He used to strip her mask away

1594
01:51:57,834 --> 01:52:01,747
"And when at last the dance was done
He glowed as if he knew he'd won

1595
01:52:02,514 --> 01:52:05,506
"And with a voice too eager
And a smile too broad

1596
01:52:05,994 --> 01:52:09,191
"He announced to the hostess
That she was a fraud"

1597
01:52:10,234 --> 01:52:11,269
No!

1598
01:52:16,714 --> 01:52:20,946
"'Her English is too good,' he said
'That clearly indicates that she is foreign

1599
01:52:22,954 --> 01:52:25,627
"'Whereas others are instructed
ln their native language

1600
01:52:25,714 --> 01:52:27,432
"'English people aren't

1601
01:52:29,034 --> 01:52:33,505
"'Although she may have studied with
an expert dialectician and grammarian

1602
01:52:35,594 --> 01:52:40,031
"'l can tell that she was born

1603
01:52:41,434 --> 01:52:42,753
"'Hungarian"'

1604
01:52:42,874 --> 01:52:44,023
[Laughing]

1605
01:52:44,154 --> 01:52:46,509
"Not only Hungarian but of royal blood

1606
01:52:47,594 --> 01:52:49,266
"She is a princess

1607
01:52:49,834 --> 01:52:53,509
"'Her blood,' he said
'ls bluer than the Danube is or ever was

1608
01:52:53,634 --> 01:52:56,467
"'Royalty is absolutely written on her face

1609
01:52:56,554 --> 01:52:59,466
"'She thought l was taken in
But actually l never was

1610
01:52:59,594 --> 01:53:02,472
"'How could she deceive
Another member of her race?

1611
01:53:02,994 --> 01:53:07,192
"'l know each language on the map'
Said he

1612
01:53:07,434 --> 01:53:10,904
"'And she's Hungarian
As the first Hungarian Rhapsody"'

1613
01:53:11,674 --> 01:53:13,027
[Laughing]

1614
01:53:19,234 --> 01:53:22,783
SERVANTS: [Singing] "Congratulations,
Professor Higgins

1615
01:53:23,274 --> 01:53:26,505
"For your glorious victory

1616
01:53:26,874 --> 01:53:30,344
"Congratulations, Professor Higgins

1617
01:53:30,874 --> 01:53:34,184
"You'll be mentioned in history"

1618
01:53:35,994 --> 01:53:38,064
[Singing continues]

1619
01:53:55,954 --> 01:53:58,070
Well, thank God, that's over.

1620
01:53:58,594 --> 01:54:01,188
Now l can go to bed
without dreading tomorrow.

1621
01:54:02,314 --> 01:54:05,750
MRS. PEARCE: Good night, Mr. Higgins.
HENRY: Good night, Mrs. Pearce.

1622
01:54:05,834 --> 01:54:09,543
PlCKERlNG: l think l'll turn in, too.
Good night. lt's been a great occasion.

1623
01:54:09,634 --> 01:54:11,192
Good night, Pickering.

1624
01:54:12,074 --> 01:54:13,348
Mrs. Pearce?

1625
01:54:14,234 --> 01:54:18,273
Damn, l meant to ask her to give me coffee
in the morning instead of tea.

1626
01:54:18,874 --> 01:54:22,549
Leave a little note for her will you, Eliza.
And put out the lights.

1627
01:54:51,274 --> 01:54:53,105
[Eliza gasps and sobs]

1628
01:55:08,354 --> 01:55:10,822
HENRY: Must be downstairs. Oh, darn it.

1629
01:55:11,194 --> 01:55:12,946
I'll leave my head behind
one of these days.

1630
01:55:13,034 --> 01:55:15,548
What the devil have I done
with my slippers?

1631
01:55:18,154 --> 01:55:20,145
[Shouts] Here are your slippers!

1632
01:55:21,314 --> 01:55:22,542
[Eliza shrieks]

1633
01:55:24,874 --> 01:55:28,503
Take your slippers and may you never
have a day's luck with them.

1634
01:55:29,194 --> 01:55:31,105
What on earth? What's the matter?

1635
01:55:31,194 --> 01:55:32,786
ls anything wrong?

1636
01:55:32,914 --> 01:55:35,747
No, nothing's wrong with you.
l won your bet for you, haven't l?

1637
01:55:35,834 --> 01:55:38,587
That's enough for you!
l don't matter, l suppose?

1638
01:55:39,154 --> 01:55:42,430
You won my bet?
You presumptuous insect! l won it!

1639
01:55:42,714 --> 01:55:44,306
Why did you throw the slippers at me?

1640
01:55:44,394 --> 01:55:47,704
Because l wanted to smash your face.
l could kill you, you selfish brute!

1641
01:55:47,794 --> 01:55:49,864
Why didn't you leave me
where you picked me up?

1642
01:55:49,954 --> 01:55:53,583
You thank God it's all over. Now you can
throw me back again! Do you?

1643
01:55:53,674 --> 01:55:56,142
Oh, so the creature's nervous after all?

1644
01:55:56,954 --> 01:55:58,387
[Eliza shrieks]

1645
01:55:59,274 --> 01:56:01,742
Claws in, you cat!
How dare you show your temper to me?

1646
01:56:01,834 --> 01:56:03,347
Sit down and be quiet!

1647
01:56:03,434 --> 01:56:05,664
[Sobs] What's to become of me?

1648
01:56:08,994 --> 01:56:10,825
How do l know what's to become of you?

1649
01:56:10,914 --> 01:56:12,063
What does it matter?

1650
01:56:12,154 --> 01:56:14,714
You don't care. l know you don't care.

1651
01:56:14,794 --> 01:56:17,183
You wouldn't care if l was dead.
l'm nothing to you.

1652
01:56:17,274 --> 01:56:19,071
Not as much as them slippers.

1653
01:56:19,154 --> 01:56:20,189
Those slippers!

1654
01:56:20,274 --> 01:56:23,789
Those slippers! l didn't think it meant
any difference now.

1655
01:56:27,234 --> 01:56:29,873
Why have you suddenly begun
going on like this?

1656
01:56:30,194 --> 01:56:32,754
May l ask if you complain
of your treatment here?

1657
01:56:32,834 --> 01:56:33,630
No.

1658
01:56:33,754 --> 01:56:36,746
Has anybody behaved badly?
Colonel Pickering, Mrs. Pearce?

1659
01:56:36,834 --> 01:56:37,823
No.

1660
01:56:38,114 --> 01:56:41,072
Well you don't pretend
that l have treated you badly?

1661
01:56:41,834 --> 01:56:42,823
No.

1662
01:56:42,914 --> 01:56:44,745
Well, l'm glad to hear that.

1663
01:56:45,714 --> 01:56:48,467
Perhaps you're tired
after the strain of the day.

1664
01:56:49,114 --> 01:56:51,184
Would you have a chocolate?

1665
01:56:51,714 --> 01:56:53,989
No, thank you.

1666
01:56:56,194 --> 01:57:00,028
Well, it's only natural that you should
be anxious, but it's all over now.

1667
01:57:00,114 --> 01:57:01,911
Nothing more to worry about.

1668
01:57:01,994 --> 01:57:04,747
No, nothing more for you to worry about.

1669
01:57:06,034 --> 01:57:08,104
Oh, God, l wish l was dead.

1670
01:57:09,234 --> 01:57:11,384
Why? ln heaven's name, why?

1671
01:57:12,514 --> 01:57:16,109
Now listen to me, Eliza.
All this irritation is purely subjective.

1672
01:57:16,474 --> 01:57:18,624
l don't understand. l'm too ignorant.

1673
01:57:18,714 --> 01:57:22,070
lt's just imagination. Nothing's wrong.
Nobody's hurting you.

1674
01:57:22,154 --> 01:57:23,303
Go to bed and sleep it off.

1675
01:57:23,394 --> 01:57:27,672
Have a little cry and say your prayers.
You'll feel very much more comfortable.

1676
01:57:27,994 --> 01:57:29,746
l heard your prayers.

1677
01:57:29,914 --> 01:57:31,586
"Thank God it's all over."

1678
01:57:31,714 --> 01:57:33,352
Don't you thank God it's all over?

1679
01:57:33,434 --> 01:57:35,743
Now you're free,
and you can do what you like.

1680
01:57:35,834 --> 01:57:38,826
Oh, what am l fit for?
What have you left me fit for?

1681
01:57:39,514 --> 01:57:41,982
Where am l to go? What am l to do?

1682
01:57:42,754 --> 01:57:44,745
And what's to become of me?

1683
01:57:45,794 --> 01:57:48,228
That's what's worrying you, is it?

1684
01:57:50,074 --> 01:57:51,951
l wouldn't worry about that if l were you.

1685
01:57:52,034 --> 01:57:56,266
l'm sure you won't have any difficulty
in settling yourself somewhere or other.

1686
01:57:58,914 --> 01:58:01,428
l didn't quite realize you were going away.

1687
01:58:02,434 --> 01:58:04,311
You might marry, you know.

1688
01:58:04,674 --> 01:58:08,428
You see, Eliza, all men are not confirmed
old bachelors like me and the Colonel.

1689
01:58:08,514 --> 01:58:11,392
Most men are the marrying sort,
poor devils.

1690
01:58:12,114 --> 01:58:13,069
You're not bad-looking.

1691
01:58:13,154 --> 01:58:15,543
You're really quite a pleasure
to look at sometimes.

1692
01:58:15,634 --> 01:58:17,113
Not now, when you've been crying.

1693
01:58:17,194 --> 01:58:18,912
You look like the very devil, but...

1694
01:58:18,994 --> 01:58:23,272
...when you're all right and quite yourself
you're what l would call attractive.

1695
01:58:25,114 --> 01:58:27,344
Go to bed, have a good rest,
get up in the morning...

1696
01:58:27,434 --> 01:58:31,063
...and have a look at yourself in the glass.
You won't feel so bad.

1697
01:58:35,354 --> 01:58:39,029
l daresay, my mother might find some
fellow or other who would do very well.

1698
01:58:39,114 --> 01:58:41,264
ELlZA: We were above that
at Covent Garden.

1699
01:58:41,354 --> 01:58:42,753
What do you mean?

1700
01:58:42,834 --> 01:58:45,268
l sold flowers, l didn't sell myself.

1701
01:58:45,994 --> 01:58:48,986
Now you've made a lady of me,
l'm not fit to sell anything else.

1702
01:58:49,074 --> 01:58:51,634
Oh, tosh, Eliza.
Don't insult human relations...

1703
01:58:51,714 --> 01:58:54,626
...by dragging all that cant
about buying and selling into it.

1704
01:58:54,714 --> 01:58:56,705
Don't marry the fellow if you don't want to.

1705
01:58:56,794 --> 01:58:58,352
What else am l to do?

1706
01:58:58,434 --> 01:59:00,186
Oh, there are lots of things.

1707
01:59:00,274 --> 01:59:02,583
What about the old idea of a florist shop?

1708
01:59:02,674 --> 01:59:05,586
l'm sure Pickering'd set you up in one.
He's got lots of money.

1709
01:59:05,674 --> 01:59:07,551
He'll pay for all those togs you're wearing.

1710
01:59:07,634 --> 01:59:11,547
And that with the hire of the jewelry'll
make a big hole in 200 pounds.

1711
01:59:11,754 --> 01:59:14,029
Come on now. You'll be all right.

1712
01:59:15,154 --> 01:59:18,191
Well, l must be off to bed.
l'm really devilish sleepy.

1713
01:59:19,474 --> 01:59:21,669
l was looking for something. What was it?

1714
01:59:21,754 --> 01:59:22,903
Your slippers.

1715
01:59:23,394 --> 01:59:26,033
Oh, yes, of course. You shied them at me.

1716
01:59:27,114 --> 01:59:29,150
ELlZA: Before you go, sir.

1717
01:59:32,914 --> 01:59:35,792
Do my clothes belong to me
or to Colonel Pickering?

1718
01:59:36,834 --> 01:59:38,950
What the devil use would they be
to Pickering?

1719
01:59:39,034 --> 01:59:40,945
Why bother about that
in the middle of the night?

1720
01:59:41,034 --> 01:59:42,433
What may l take away with me?

1721
01:59:42,514 --> 01:59:44,823
l don't want to be accused of stealing.

1722
01:59:45,474 --> 01:59:46,509
Stealing?

1723
01:59:47,554 --> 01:59:50,705
You shouldn't have said that.
That shows a want of feeling.

1724
01:59:50,794 --> 01:59:54,673
l'm sorry. l'm a common, ignorant girl
and in my station l have to be careful.

1725
01:59:54,754 --> 01:59:58,064
There can't be any feelings between
the likes of you and the likes of me.

1726
01:59:58,154 --> 02:00:01,510
Please, will you tell me
what belongs to me and what doesn't?

1727
02:00:01,954 --> 02:00:04,229
Take the whole damned houseful
if you want.

1728
02:00:04,314 --> 02:00:06,953
Except the jewelry. That's hired.
Will that satisfy you?

1729
02:00:07,034 --> 02:00:08,228
Stop, please.

1730
02:00:10,354 --> 02:00:13,585
ELlZA: Will you take these to your room
and keep them safe?

1731
02:00:14,074 --> 02:00:16,872
l don't want to run the risk
of them being missed.

1732
02:00:18,394 --> 02:00:21,750
Hand them over! lf these belonged
to me and not the jeweler, l'd...

1733
02:00:21,834 --> 02:00:24,302
...l'd ram them down
your ungrateful throat.

1734
02:00:24,594 --> 02:00:28,507
The ring isn't the jeweler's.
lt's the one you bought me in Brighton.

1735
02:00:29,794 --> 02:00:31,273
l don't want it now.

1736
02:00:34,394 --> 02:00:35,986
Don't you hit me!

1737
02:00:36,474 --> 02:00:39,511
Hit you? You infamous creature!
How dare you suggest such a thing!

1738
02:00:39,594 --> 02:00:42,154
lt's you who've hit me.
You've wounded me to the heart.

1739
02:00:42,234 --> 02:00:45,510
l'm glad. l've got a little
of my own back anyhow.

1740
02:00:46,794 --> 02:00:50,230
You've caused me to lose my temper.
That's hardly happened to me before.

1741
02:00:50,314 --> 02:00:52,987
l don't wish to discuss it further tonight.
l'm going to bed.

1742
02:00:53,074 --> 02:00:55,542
ELlZA: Leave your own note
about the coffee...

1743
02:00:55,634 --> 02:00:57,147
...for it won't be done by me!

1744
02:00:57,234 --> 02:01:00,271
Damn Mrs. Pearce,
damn the coffee and damn you!

1745
02:01:01,874 --> 02:01:04,991
Damn my own folly for having lavished
my hard-earned knowledge...

1746
02:01:05,074 --> 02:01:09,067
...and the treasure of my regard
and intimacy on a heartless guttersnipe!

1747
02:01:10,074 --> 02:01:13,066
[Vowels spoken in Henry's voice
droning on phonograph]

1748
02:01:23,074 --> 02:01:25,065
[Melancholic instrumental music]

1749
02:01:58,234 --> 02:02:02,546
[Sings] "Just you wait, 'Enry 'lggins
Just you wait!

1750
02:02:04,554 --> 02:02:07,671
"You'll be sorry
But your tears will be too late

1751
02:02:10,554 --> 02:02:12,943
"You will be the one it's done to

1752
02:02:14,074 --> 02:02:16,463
"And you'll have no one to run to

1753
02:02:17,754 --> 02:02:19,267
"Just you wait"

1754
02:02:46,794 --> 02:02:51,345
FREDDY: [Sings] "l have often walked
down this street before

1755
02:02:52,314 --> 02:02:56,944
"But the pavement always stayed
beneath my feet before

1756
02:02:57,834 --> 02:03:02,669
"All at once am l several stories high

1757
02:03:03,434 --> 02:03:07,825
"Knowing l'm on the street where you live

1758
02:03:09,194 --> 02:03:13,745
"Are there lilac trees in the heart of town?

1759
02:03:14,794 --> 02:03:19,424
"Can you hear a lark
in any other part of town?

1760
02:03:20,554 --> 02:03:25,503
"Does enchantment pour
out of every door?

1761
02:03:26,234 --> 02:03:30,512
"No, it's just on the street where you live

1762
02:03:32,034 --> 02:03:36,266
"And, oh, the towering feeling

1763
02:03:37,354 --> 02:03:41,791
"Just to know somehow you are near

1764
02:03:43,434 --> 02:03:47,632
"The overpowering feeling

1765
02:03:48,314 --> 02:03:52,865
"That any second you may suddenly appear

1766
02:03:54,434 --> 02:03:57,107
"People stop and stare, they don't.... "

1767
02:04:04,034 --> 02:04:05,023
Darling.

1768
02:04:06,394 --> 02:04:08,066
Freddy, whatever are you doing here?

1769
02:04:08,154 --> 02:04:11,863
Nothing. l spend most of my nights here.
lt's the only place where l'm happy.

1770
02:04:11,954 --> 02:04:13,512
Don't laugh at me, Miss Doolittle.

1771
02:04:13,594 --> 02:04:17,746
Don't you call me "Miss Doolittle,"
do you hear? Eliza's good enough for me.

1772
02:04:19,594 --> 02:04:23,030
Freddy, you don't think
l'm a heartless guttersnipe, do you?

1773
02:04:23,114 --> 02:04:26,072
Darling, how could you imagine
such a thing? You know how l feel.

1774
02:04:26,154 --> 02:04:29,464
l've written two and three times a day
telling you. Sheets and sheets.

1775
02:04:29,554 --> 02:04:32,671
[Sings] "Speak, and the world
is full of singing

1776
02:04:32,954 --> 02:04:36,833
"And l am winging higher than the birds

1777
02:04:38,154 --> 02:04:40,793
"Touch, and my heart begins to crumble

1778
02:04:41,834 --> 02:04:44,473
"The heavens tumble
Darling, and l'm--"

1779
02:04:45,634 --> 02:04:48,512
"Words, words, words
l'm so sick of words

1780
02:04:48,674 --> 02:04:51,711
"l get words all day through
First from him, now from you

1781
02:04:51,794 --> 02:04:54,228
"ls that all you blighters can do?

1782
02:04:56,434 --> 02:04:58,868
"Don't talk of stars burning above

1783
02:04:59,634 --> 02:05:01,704
"lf you're in love, show me

1784
02:05:02,834 --> 02:05:05,428
"Tell me no dreams filled with desire

1785
02:05:06,034 --> 02:05:08,104
"lf you're on fire, show me

1786
02:05:09,114 --> 02:05:11,389
"Here we are together
ln the middle of the night

1787
02:05:11,474 --> 02:05:14,147
"Don't talk of spring
Just hold me tight

1788
02:05:15,394 --> 02:05:17,624
"Anyone who's ever been in love'll
Tell you that

1789
02:05:17,714 --> 02:05:19,591
"This is no time for a chat

1790
02:05:21,714 --> 02:05:24,387
"Haven't your lips longed for my touch?

1791
02:05:24,954 --> 02:05:27,104
"Don't say how much, show me

1792
02:05:27,914 --> 02:05:29,142
"Show me

1793
02:05:29,754 --> 02:05:32,507
"Don't talk of love lasting through time

1794
02:05:33,074 --> 02:05:34,985
"Make me no undying vow

1795
02:05:36,234 --> 02:05:40,227
"Show me now

1796
02:05:42,594 --> 02:05:45,028
"Sing me no song, read me no rhyme

1797
02:05:45,754 --> 02:05:47,949
"Don't waste my time, show me

1798
02:05:49,074 --> 02:05:51,747
"Don't talk of June, don't talk of fall

1799
02:05:52,354 --> 02:05:54,424
"Don't talk at all, show me

1800
02:05:55,634 --> 02:05:57,829
"Never do l ever
want to hear another word

1801
02:05:57,914 --> 02:06:01,224
"There isn't one l haven't heard

1802
02:06:01,994 --> 02:06:04,349
"Here we are together
in what ought to be a dream

1803
02:06:04,434 --> 02:06:06,868
"Say one more word and l'll scream

1804
02:06:08,474 --> 02:06:11,068
"Haven't your arms hungered for mine?

1805
02:06:11,754 --> 02:06:13,984
"Please don't explain, show me

1806
02:06:14,754 --> 02:06:15,982
"Show me

1807
02:06:16,674 --> 02:06:19,188
"Don't wait until wrinkles and lines

1808
02:06:19,914 --> 02:06:21,905
"Pop out all over my brow

1809
02:06:23,154 --> 02:06:27,227
"Show me now! "

1810
02:06:31,554 --> 02:06:33,226
-Where are you going?
-To the river.

1811
02:06:33,314 --> 02:06:35,305
-What for?
-To make a hole in it.

1812
02:06:36,794 --> 02:06:38,864
Eliza, darling, what do you mean?

1813
02:06:39,354 --> 02:06:41,345
[Melancholic instrumental music]

1814
02:06:48,034 --> 02:06:49,149
Taxi!

1815
02:06:50,674 --> 02:06:52,551
-But l've no money.
-l have.

1816
02:06:52,874 --> 02:06:55,672
FREDDY: Where are we going?
ELlZA: Where l belong.

1817
02:07:09,234 --> 02:07:11,190
Darling, shall l come with you?

1818
02:07:28,074 --> 02:07:31,544
[Whistling to cheerful tune of
Wouldn't It Be Loverly?]

1819
02:07:36,594 --> 02:07:39,233
MAN'S VOlCE: [Singing]
"With one enormous chair

1820
02:07:40,074 --> 02:07:42,224
"Oh, wouldn't it be loverly?

1821
02:07:45,394 --> 02:07:47,783
CHORUS: "Lots of chocolate for me to eat

1822
02:07:50,194 --> 02:07:52,583
"Lots of coal makin' lots of 'eat

1823
02:07:55,514 --> 02:07:57,903
"Warm face, warm 'ands, warm feet

1824
02:07:59,114 --> 02:08:01,309
"Oh, wouldn't it be loverly?"

1825
02:08:06,114 --> 02:08:07,547
Buy a flower, miss?

1826
02:08:08,914 --> 02:08:10,063
Yes, please.

1827
02:08:14,274 --> 02:08:16,230
[Singing continues, background]

1828
02:08:45,634 --> 02:08:47,784
Good morning, miss. Can l help you?

1829
02:08:50,994 --> 02:08:52,950
Do you mind if l warm my hands?

1830
02:08:53,074 --> 02:08:54,587
Go right ahead, miss.

1831
02:09:01,794 --> 02:09:02,624
Yes?

1832
02:09:02,834 --> 02:09:05,587
Excuse me. For a second
l thought you were somebody else.

1833
02:09:05,674 --> 02:09:06,629
Who?

1834
02:09:07,194 --> 02:09:10,743
Forgive me, ma'am. Early morning light
playing tricks with my eyes.

1835
02:09:10,834 --> 02:09:13,632
Can l get you a taxi?
A lady shouldn't be walkin' alone...

1836
02:09:13,714 --> 02:09:16,182
...around London this hour of the morning.

1837
02:09:17,714 --> 02:09:19,067
No, thank you.

1838
02:09:28,154 --> 02:09:31,385
ELlZA'S VOlCE: [Singing]
"Someone's head restin' on my knee

1839
02:09:32,314 --> 02:09:34,509
"Warm and tender as he can be

1840
02:09:37,034 --> 02:09:39,070
"Who takes good care of me

1841
02:09:40,354 --> 02:09:42,072
"Oh, wouldn't it...

1842
02:09:44,594 --> 02:09:46,107
"...be loverly?

1843
02:09:47,794 --> 02:09:49,068
"Loverly "

1844
02:10:03,634 --> 02:10:07,673
BARTENDER: Do come again, Mr. Doolittle.
We value your patronage always.

1845
02:10:07,754 --> 02:10:10,666
Thank you, my good man. Thank you.
Here. Come 'ere.

1846
02:10:11,434 --> 02:10:13,902
Take the missus on a trip to Brighton
with my compliments.

1847
02:10:13,994 --> 02:10:15,746
BARTENDER: Thank you, Mr. Doolittle.

1848
02:10:15,834 --> 02:10:16,903
[Laughter]

1849
02:10:16,994 --> 02:10:20,031
Jolly spot this, Harry.
We must visit it more often.

1850
02:10:20,994 --> 02:10:21,904
Father?

1851
02:10:24,074 --> 02:10:26,872
Oh, no. You see, Harry, he has no mercy.

1852
02:10:27,554 --> 02:10:31,467
Sent her down to spy on me in me misery,
he did. Me own flesh and blood.

1853
02:10:34,314 --> 02:10:37,272
Well, l'm miserable, all right.
You can tell him that straight.

1854
02:10:37,354 --> 02:10:39,914
What are you talking about?
What are you dressed up for?

1855
02:10:39,994 --> 02:10:41,347
As if you didn't know.

1856
02:10:41,434 --> 02:10:45,268
Go on back to that Wimpole Street devil.
Tell him what he's done to me.

1857
02:10:45,474 --> 02:10:47,032
What's he done to you?

1858
02:10:47,434 --> 02:10:48,628
Ruined me, that's all.

1859
02:10:48,714 --> 02:10:52,389
Tied me up and delivered me
into the hands of middle-class morality.

1860
02:10:52,794 --> 02:10:54,113
And don't you defend him.

1861
02:10:54,194 --> 02:10:58,551
Was it 'im or was it not 'im wrote to an old
American blighter named Wallingford...

1862
02:10:58,634 --> 02:11:02,547
...who was giving $5,000,000
to found Moral Reform societies...

1863
02:11:03,114 --> 02:11:07,505
...to tell him the most original moralist
in England was Mr. Alfred P. Doolittle...

1864
02:11:07,594 --> 02:11:09,073
...a common dustman?

1865
02:11:10,514 --> 02:11:12,391
Sounds like one of his jokes.

1866
02:11:12,554 --> 02:11:15,626
You may call it a joke.
lt's put the lid on me. Proper.

1867
02:11:15,914 --> 02:11:19,987
The old bloke died and left me
4,000 pounds a year in his bloomin' will.

1868
02:11:21,354 --> 02:11:25,313
Who asked him to make a gentleman
outta me? l was 'appy. l was free.

1869
02:11:25,874 --> 02:11:29,913
l touched pretty nigh everyone for money
when l wanted it, same as l touched him.

1870
02:11:29,994 --> 02:11:33,350
Now l'm tied neck and 'eels
and everybody touches me.

1871
02:11:34,154 --> 02:11:36,907
A year ago l 'adn't a relation in the world...

1872
02:11:37,594 --> 02:11:39,585
...except one or two
who wouldn't speak to me.

1873
02:11:39,674 --> 02:11:43,144
Now l've 50. Not a decent week's wages
amongst the lot of them.

1874
02:11:43,754 --> 02:11:48,032
l have to live for others now,
not for meself. Middle-class morality.

1875
02:11:48,914 --> 02:11:52,111
Come on, Alfie, in a few hours
we have to be at the church.

1876
02:11:52,194 --> 02:11:54,025
-Church?
-Yeah, church.

1877
02:11:55,274 --> 02:11:57,105
The deepest cut of all.

1878
02:11:57,594 --> 02:12:00,666
Why do you think l'm dressed up
like a ruddy pallbearer?

1879
02:12:01,194 --> 02:12:03,025
Your stepmother wants to marry me.

1880
02:12:03,114 --> 02:12:05,833
Now l'm respectable,
she wants to be respectable.

1881
02:12:05,914 --> 02:12:09,350
ELlZA: lf that's the way you feel,
why don't you give the money back?

1882
02:12:09,434 --> 02:12:11,425
